HW 3 Bolin Ji 2/2/2018

Executive Summary

In this homework, we wish to find out the annual return of every stock in order to develop certain basic intuition about the stock market based on winners and losers every year. By purely looking at the basic characteristics of winners and losers, we could propose hypothesis and test hypothesis from further studies. On the other hand, we could also look at the performance of stocks relative to the performance of other stocks. Also, based on this dataset, I want to explore the market return in the past 90 years if the market index is equally weighted, and find the difference between equally weighted index and value weighted index. As a reuslt, we found that the equally weighted index had a return of 158.96% in 1954, which is impressive. However, the downside would also be larger. During 2009 to 2010, when the value weighted index turns positive after the financial crisis, the equally weighted portfolio still suffer from a negative return of -9.35%

Here is the annual return of each stock, and you could searh by CUSIP,PERMNO or TICKER. https://github.com/jbl410909/corp-fin/raw/master/annual%20return.zip

Full Body Text

1. Concepts

Annual Return: The return of a given stock in any given year. If the stock is only listed for several days, we should consider the stock as well. On the other hand, to mimic the holding period return of a client, we used the geometric compounded return, which takes the product of all holding period gains and losses.

Equally weighted portfolio: we assume we would put in equal amount of money in the portfolio, then the portfolio return would just be the arithmetic average return, which is given by the following formula. \[A=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^nR_i\]

2. Assumptions

Stock: In this case, we assume the stocks should all be past or present stocks that has been traded for two practical reason. First, we would like to contradict the value weighted index by giving larger weight on smaller stocks. Second, we want to make sure the index is comprehensive enough so that we would not miss any individual sample

Data Frame: In this case, we use the stock return from 1926 to 2016 to look at the historical perforamcnce.

3. Data Source

In this case, we used data from WRDS->CRSP->Annual Update->Stock->Security Files->CRSP Daily Stock. Data was selected from 1926-01-01 to 2016-12-31, and we searched the entire database with Query Variables Ticker, Holding Period Return,Return on S&P Composite, Price,Shares Oustanding,CUSIP.

4. Coding Process

1.Data Segregation: Due to hardware constrains, my laptop could not read data greater than 1 GB. In order to tackle the issue and finish this homework efficiently, I dividend the data into 14 smaller subsets based on dates, and then computed the annual return for each of them.

2.Data Cleansing: First, we import our data from CSV file, then we would reformate the data with respective columns. For return, market return, and dividend, we would format them as numerical value. For Ticker, we would format them as text. Then, we would compute the difference between stock return and market return, and save the excess return as a column of the data. Since return that is reported as B or C or N/A is useless, we would filter the data by deleting all non-numerical return from the data.

  1. Return Computation: In order to compute the return, I first formatted the date into Year format, then I tried to look for the beginning and the ending of the year. To extract one security out of the entire sample, I would find the first and the last of the location of a given PERMNO, then I compute the annual return for each of the PERMNO, at the end, I would have a table for that period of year.

  2. Result Matching: To match multiple tables together, I first went through all the table to find the total unique PERMNOs in the table. Then I would start a search process with a big matrix. When the PERMNO from the entire matrix is matched with the PERMNO of the small matrix, that location would be filled. At the end, we would have a large matrix with year on the horizontal axis and PERMNO on the vertical axis.

library(xts)
library(grid)
library(gridExtra)
library(data.table)
#read data into R
stock1<-read.csv(file="C:/Users/kuku/Desktop/MFE/Corp Fin/stock1.csv",header=TRUE)
stock1<-as.data.frame(stock1)
stock1$date<-as.Date(stock1$date,format="%m/%d/%Y")
stock1$date<-format(stock1$date,"%Y")
stock1$PERMNO<-as.character(stock1$PERMNO)
stock1$CUSIP<-as.character(stock1$CUSIP)
stock1$sprtrn<-as.numeric(as.character(stock1$sprtrn))
stock1$RET<-as.numeric(as.character(stock1$RET))
stock1$PRC<-abs(as.numeric(as.character(stock1$PRC)))
stock1=stock1[which(stock1$RET>-1),]
perm<-unique(stock1$PERMNO)
n<-length(perm)
yearval<-as.numeric(unique(stock1$date))
ny<-length(yearval)
history<-as.matrix(yearval,ncol=1,byrow=TRUE)
history<-rbind("Description","Year",history)
for (i in 1:n){
  tempo<-c()
  ryear<-c()
  cap<-c()
  a<-max(which(stock1$PERMNO==perm[i]))
  g<-min(which(stock1$PERMNO==perm[i]))
  tempo<-stock1[g:a,]
  counter=1
  uyear<-as.numeric(unique(tempo$date))
  for (j in 1:ny){
    if(uyear[counter]==yearval[j]&&counter<=length(uyear)){
    sy<-min(which(tempo$date==yearval[j]))
    ey<-max(which(tempo$date==yearval[j]))
    ryear[j]<-prod(1+tempo$RET[sy:ny])-1
    cap[j]<-mean(tempo$SHROUT[sy:ny])*mean(tempo$PRC[sy:ny])
    counter=counter+1
    }
    else{
      ryear[j]=0
      cap[j]=0
    }
  }
  d<-cbind(" ",tempo$CUSIP[1])
  e<-cbind(tempo$TICKER[1],tempo$PERMNO[1])
  f<-cbind(ryear,cap)
  his<-rbind(d,e,f)
  history<-cbind(x=history,y=his)
}
write.csv(history,file="C:/Users/kuku/Desktop/MFE/Corp Fin/stock1s.csv")
rm(list=ls())

stock11<-read.csv(file="C:/Users/kuku/Desktop/MFE/Corp Fin/stock11.csv",header=TRUE)
stock11<-as.data.frame(stock11)
stock11$date<-as.Date(stock11$date,format="%m/%d/%Y")
stock11$date<-format(stock11$date,"%Y")
stock11$PERMNO<-as.character(stock11$PERMNO)
stock11$CUSIP<-as.character(stock11$CUSIP)
stock11$sprtrn<-as.numeric(as.character(stock11$sprtrn))
stock11$RET<-as.numeric(as.character(stock11$RET))
stock11$PRC<-abs(as.numeric(as.character(stock11$PRC)))
stock11=stock11[which(stock11$RET>-1),]
perm<-unique(stock11$PERMNO)
n<-length(perm)
yearval<-as.numeric(unique(stock11$date))
ny<-length(yearval)
history<-as.matrix(yearval,ncol=1,byrow=TRUE)
history<-rbind("Description","Year",history)
for (i in 1:n){
  tempo<-c()
  ryear<-c()
  cap<-c()
  a<-max(which(stock11$PERMNO==perm[i]))
  g<-min(which(stock11$PERMNO==perm[i]))
  tempo<-stock11[g:a,]
  counter=1
  uyear<-as.numeric(unique(tempo$date))
  for (j in 1:ny){
    if(uyear[counter]==yearval[j]&&counter<=length(uyear)){
      sy<-min(which(tempo$date==yearval[j]))
      ey<-max(which(tempo$date==yearval[j]))
      ryear[j]<-prod(1+tempo$RET[sy:ny])-1
      cap[j]<-mean(tempo$SHROUT[sy:ny])*mean(tempo$PRC[sy:ny])
      counter=counter+1
    }
    else{
      ryear[j]=0
      cap[j]=0
    }
  }
  d<-cbind(" ",tempo$CUSIP[1])
  e<-cbind(tempo$TICKER[1],tempo$PERMNO[1])
  f<-cbind(ryear,cap)
  his<-rbind(d,e,f)
  history<-cbind(x=history,y=his)
}
write.csv(history,file="C:/Users/kuku/Desktop/MFE/Corp Fin/stock11s.csv")
